abstract: China's currency and free-trade agreements will come up for votes. But President Obama's jobs bill is unlikely to move forward.
snippet: China's currency and free-trade agreements will come up for votes. But President Obama's jobs bill is unlikely to move forward.
lead_paragraph: After a bit of unpleasantness on the Senate floor last week, members are expected to come together Tuesday to pass a bill to impose tariffs on some Chinese goods to punish Beijing for keeping its currency artificially depressed. The bill has a slim chance of ever being taken up in the House, where Democrats are pushing Republicans to consider the measure.
